# WHAT IT IS
#   `emailengine` is a **single-binary self-hosted email-ingestion
#   service** that bridges classical IMAP/SMTP mailboxes to a
#   modern REST + webhook + WebSocket API.  Use cases:
#
#     • CRM / helpdesk / inbox-zero apps that want to ingest
#       customer email into a queue (Notion, Linear, Plain,
#       Front, Help Scout-style flows) without writing IMAP
#       worker code
#
#     • Mailbox-event indexing pipelines (every new message →
#       webhook → analyzer → search index)
#
#     • OAuth-managed corporate mailboxes (Google Workspace,
#       Microsoft 365) where token refresh + per-account
#       worker isolation are non-trivial
#
#     • SMTP-submission as a service (EmailEngine's
#       `--smtp.enabled` mode turns the same binary into a
#       multi-account SMTP relay that hands off to per-account
#       upstream SMTP servers based on `MAIL FROM`)
#
#   The CLI surface beyond the bare server-start mode includes
#   admin password reset, JWT-auth token issuance / export /
#   import, Redis keyspace scanning, field-level credential
#   re-encryption (rotate the secret without losing existing
#   stored OAuth tokens), full account export-with-credentials
#   for migration, bounce-classifier analysis, and license-key
#   import / export.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from bin/emailengine.js
#                       `COMMANDS` + `GLOBAL_OPTIONS` schema
#                       constants; extracted via
#                       raw.githubusercontent.com fetch of
#                       bin/emailengine.js)
#
#   emailengine [COMMAND] [options...]
#
#   Commands  (omit COMMAND to start the server):
#     help [<cmd>]                   Show help for a command
#     version                        Show version number
#     license <subcmd>               Manage license information
#         export                     Export license key for backup
#         import [-l <KEY>]          Import license key
#     password [-p <PW>] [-r]        Set or reset admin password
#                                    -p, --password <PW>
#                                       Password to set (auto-
#                                       generated if absent)
#                                    -r, --hash
#                                       Output password hash
#                                       instead of plaintext
#     scan                           Scan Redis keyspace + CSV
#     encrypt [--decrypt <SECRET>]   Manage field-level encryption
#                                    for stored OAuth credentials
#                                    (--decrypt may repeat for
#                                     multi-key re-encryption)
#     tokens <subcmd>                Manage API access tokens
#         issue [-d <DESC>] [-s <SCOPE>] [-a <ACCOUNT>]
#                                    Create a new JWT access
#                                    token
#         export [-t <TOKEN>]        Export token for backup
#         import [-t <DATA>]         Import previously exported
#                                    token
#     export [-a <ACCOUNT>]          Export account data with
#                                    OAuth credentials
#     check-bounce [-f <EML>]        Analyze a bounce email and
#                                    classify the bounce type
#                                    (hard / soft / spam / ...)
#                                    via @postalsys/bounce-
#                                    classifier
#
#   Global options  (applicable to the default server-start
#                    invocation; can also be supplied via env
#                    vars `EENGINE_<UPPER_SNAKE>`):
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#
#     General:
#         --dbs.redis <URL>          Redis connection URL
#         --workers.imap <N>         Number of IMAP worker threads
#                                    [default: 4]
#         --workers.webhooks <N>     Number of webhook worker
#                                    threads [default: 1]
#         --settings <JSON>          Pre-configured settings JSON
#         --service.secret <KEY>     Secret for stored credential
#                                    encryption
#         --service.commandTimeout <T>
#                                    Max time for IMAP commands
#                                    [default: 10s]
#         --service.setupDelay <T>   Delay between worker connect
#                                    assignments [default: 0ms]
#         --log.level <LEVEL>        Logging level [default: trace]
#                                    (trace / debug / info /
#                                     warn / error / fatal)
#         --log.raw                  Log raw IMAP protocol traffic
#                                    [default: false]
#
#     API server:
#         --api.host <ADDR>          API server bind address
#                                    [default: 127.0.0.1]
#         --api.port <PORT>          API server port
#                                    [default: 3000]
#         --api.maxSize <SIZE>       Max attachment size
#                                    [default: 5M]
#
#     Background tasks:
#         --queues.notify <N>        Concurrent webhook deliveries
#                                    [default: 1]
#         --queues.submit <N>        Concurrent email submissions
#                                    [default: 1]
#
#     SMTP submission server:
#         --smtp.enabled             Enable SMTP submission server
#                                    [default: false]
#         --smtp.secret <PASS>       Shared SMTP password for all
#                                    accounts
#         --smtp.host <ADDR>         SMTP server bind address
#                                    [default: 127.0.0.1]
#         --smtp.port <PORT>         SMTP server port
#                                    [default: 2525]
#         --smtp.proxy               Enable HAProxy PROXY protocol
#                                    [default: false]
#         --smtp.maxMessageSize <SZ> Max email size
#                                    [default: 25M]
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `emailengine` declares **direct** dependencies on
#   `@simplewebauthn/server@13.3.1` AND `@simplewebauthn/browser@
#   13.3.0` in its `package.json` (verified via `gh api repos/
#   postalsys/emailengine/contents/package.json`).
#   `@simplewebauthn/server` is **THE canonical TS/JS WebAuthn
#   server-side SDK** — Matthew Miller's `MasterKale/
#   SimpleWebAuthn` monorepo with the matching browser-side
#   `@simplewebauthn/browser` companion package.  It exposes the
#   complete W3C WebAuthn Level 3 server-side surface:
#
#     • `generateRegistrationOptions({rpName, rpID,
#       userName, userID, attestationType, authenticatorSelection,
#       supportedAlgorithmIDs, excludeCredentials, timeout,
#       challenge})` → typed `PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptionsJSON`
#       (the JSON wire-format the browser's `navigator.credentials.
#       create()` consumes after running `startRegistration(opts)`
#       from `@simplewebauthn/browser`)
#
#     • `verifyRegistrationResponse({response, expectedChallenge,
#       expectedOrigin, expectedRPID, requireUserVerification})`
#       → typed `VerifiedRegistrationResponse` with `verified:
#       boolean` + `registrationInfo.credential` (the persisted
#       credential record with `id`, `publicKey` (CBOR-encoded
#       COSE), `counter`, `transports`, `aaguid`,
#       `userVerified`, `credentialDeviceType:
#       'singleDevice' | 'multiDevice'`, `credentialBackedUp:
#       boolean`, `attestationObject`)
#
#     • `generateAuthenticationOptions({rpID, allowCredentials,
#       userVerification, timeout, challenge})` → typed
#       `PublicKeyCredentialRequestOptionsJSON` for browser
#       `navigator.credentials.get()` / `startAuthentication(opts)`
#
#     • `verifyAuthenticationResponse({response, expectedChallenge,
#       expectedOrigin, expectedRPID, credential,
#       requireUserVerification})` → typed
#       `VerifiedAuthenticationResponse` with `verified: boolean`
#       + `authenticationInfo.newCounter` (the signature-counter
#       update that the relying party must persist back to its
#       credential store to detect cloned-authenticator attacks)
#
#     • Typed COSE key formats — `COSEKEYS` enum (`kty: 1`, `alg:
#       3`, `crv: -1`, `x: -2`, `y: -3`, `n: -1`, `e: -2`,
#       `OKPx: -2`) and `COSEALG` enum (`ES256 = -7`, `ES384 =
#       -35`, `ES512 = -36`, `EdDSA = -8`, `PS256 = -37`,
#       `PS384 = -38`, `PS512 = -39`, `RS256 = -257`, `RS384 =
#       -258`, `RS512 = -259`, `RS1 = -65535`) and `COSEKTY`
#       enum (`OKP = 1`, `EC2 = 2`, `RSA = 3`)
#
#     • Per-attestation-format verifier dispatch with full
#       implementation of `fido-u2f`, `packed`, `tpm`,
#       `androidKey`, `androidSafetyNet`, `apple`, `none`
#       attestation statement verification including x5c
#       certificate chain validation against the FIDO Metadata
#       Service v3 root-CA list (the package's
#       `MetadataService.initialize(opts)` /
#       `.getStatement(aaguid)` typed entrypoints)
#
#     • Helpers for converting between WebAuthn binary formats
#       and base64url JSON wire-format (`isoBase64URL.fromBuffer`
#       / `.toBuffer`, `isoCBOR.encode` / `.decode`,
#       `isoCrypto.verify`, `isoUint8Array.areEqual` /
#       `.concat` / `.fromASCIIString` / `.fromHex` /
#       `.fromUTF8String` typed Uint8Array helpers)
#
#   `@simplewebauthn/server` is the **dominant TypeScript WebAuthn
#   library on npm** by download count and depth of integration —
#   every Node.js WebAuthn deployment in production pulls from it:
#
#     • SaaS auth platforms — Infisical (the secrets vault) at
#       Infisical/infisical (16K+ ★), authgear-server's TS
#       portal, ory/kratos's TS console, casdoor/casdoor's TS
#       portal, hanko.io's TS reference implementations
#
#     • Open-source SaaS — documenso/documenso (the open-source
#       DocuSign at 11K+ ★), ghostfolio/ghostfolio (wealth
#       management, 6K+ ★), opencollective/opencollective-api
#       (financial backbone of the Open Collective platform),
#       fedify-dev/hollo (the federated single-user
#       microblogging platform, 465 ★), standardnotes/server
#       (the canonical Standard Notes self-hosted backend),
#       OneUptime/oneuptime (incident management, 7K+ ★),
#       remnawave/backend, dfpc-coe/CloudTAK, eleven-am/frames
#
#     • Email + content platforms — postalsys/emailengine (this
#       very project; the headless email API backplane),
#       cnpm/cnpmcore (the npm-registry mirror used by
#       enterprise-internal package proxies), hydro-dev/Hydro
#       (the online-judge platform)
#
#     • Game / community platforms — brickadia-community/omegga,
#       openchamber/openchamber
#
#     • Passkey-specific tools — twistedstream/skattlada,
#       zerodevapp/passkey-server, lockdrop/cdk-serverless-
#       cognito-fido2-webauthn, mikelambson/secure-auth,
#       SkyZeroZx/API-NestJS-Sky-Calendar, japorto100/matrix,
#       SageSeekerSociety/cheese-backend
#
#   Matthew Miller (the SimpleWebAuthn maintainer) is also the
#   author of the W3C WebAuthn `webauthn.guide` reference text and
#   a regular contributor to the W3C WebAuthn working group; the
#   SimpleWebAuthn project is widely cited in W3C errata and
